---
 doc/releases/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md | 98 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 98 insertions(+)

diff --git a/doc/releases/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/doc/releases/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
index d4f8c9a12..e5f9d0b23 100644
--- a/doc/releases/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
+++ b/doc/releases/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -295,0 +1,98 @@
+
+---
+
+# Why You Cannot Fix `curl` CVE-2023-23915 via Code Patching in Containers
+
+## Overview: What Is CVE-2023-23915?
+
+CVE-2023-23915 is a vulnerability in curl versions 7.77.0 through 7.87.0 related to HSTS (HTTP Strict Transport Security) functionality. The issue causes curl's HSTS cache saving to behave incorrectly when multiple URLs are requested in parallel using `--parallel`. The HSTS cache file gets overwritten by the most recently completed transfer, causing earlier hostnames to lose their HSTS records and potentially allowing cleartext transmission of sensitive information.
+
+**Technical Details:**
+- **Component:** HSTS functionality in curl command line tool (does NOT affect libcurl)
+- **Issue:** HSTS cache file overwritten during parallel transfers; earlier hostnames lose HSTS records
+- **Impact:** HTTP-only transfers may fail to upgrade to HTTPS, leading to potential cleartext transmission
+- **Affected Versions:** curl 7.77.0 through 7.87.0 (with HSTS support enabled)
+
+---
+
+## Why CVE-2023-23915 Is a **FALSE POSITIVE** for Debian Bullseye
+
+### 🔹 1. HSTS Support Not Compiled in Debian Bullseye
+
+According to the [Debian Security Tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2023-23915):
+
+- **Debian bullseye**: curl 7.74.0-1.3+deb11u16 - **`<ignored>` (curl is not built with HSTS support)**
+- **Status**: The vulnerable HSTS functionality is **not included** in the Debian bullseye curl build
+- **Conclusion**: ✅ **Cannot be exploited** - the vulnerable code path does not exist
+
+### 🔹 2. Build Configuration Excludes Vulnerable Feature
+
+- Debian bullseye's curl package was compiled **without HSTS support**
+- The vulnerable HSTS cache handling code is not present in the binary
+- curl 7.74.0 defaults to HSTS disabled at configure time; Debian does not pass `--enable-hsts`
+- Binary verification: `curl --hsts /tmp/x http://example.com` returns "the installed libcurl version doesn't support this"
+
+### 🔹 3. Version vs. Feature Mismatch
+
+- **Upstream curl.se**: CVE-2023-23915 affects 7.77.0–7.87.0 only; 7.74.0 is explicitly "Not affected"
+- **Package Version**: 7.74.0 (outside affected range AND HSTS not built)
+- **Scanner Limitation**: Tools flag based on version ranges, not compiled features
+- **Result**: False positive due to version boundary and feature absence
+
+---
+
+## **Recommended Action: Mark as False Positive**
+
+This CVE should be marked as a **False Positive** because:
+
+1. **Feature Not Built**: The HSTS functionality containing the vulnerability is not compiled into Debian bullseye curl
+2. **Code Path Unreachable**: The vulnerable HSTS cache handling during parallel transfers cannot be executed
+3. **Version Boundary**: Upstream curl explicitly lists curl < 7.77.0 as "Not affected"
+4. **No Action Required**: The vulnerability cannot be exploited as the functionality is absent
+
+## **Specific CVE Details: CVE-2023-23915**
+
+**CVE ID**: CVE-2023-23915
+**Package**: curl
+**Debian bullseye Version**: 7.74.0-1.3+deb11u16
+**Status**: **FALSE POSITIVE** - HSTS functionality not built in distribution
+
+### **Description**
+**HSTS amnesia with --parallel**
+
+curl's HSTS cache saving behaves wrongly when multiple URLs are requested in parallel. Using its HSTS support, curl can be instructed to use HTTPS instead of clear-text HTTP. The HSTS cache file gets overwritten by the most recently completed transfer, causing earlier hostnames to lose their HSTS records. A later HTTP-only transfer to those hostnames would then not get upgraded properly to HTTPS.
+
+**Technical Details:**
+- **Introduced by**: [commit 7385610](https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/7385610d0c74c6a254fea5e4cd6e1d559d848c8c) (curl-7_74_0)
+- **Shipped enabled by default from**: [commit d71ff2b](https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/d71ff2b9db566b3f) in curl 7.77.0
+- **Fixed by**: curl 7.88.0+ via [PR #10138](https://github.com/curl/curl/pull/10138)
+- **Root Cause**: HSTS state not properly shared between parallel transfers
+
+### **Why This Is a False Positive for Debian Bullseye**
+1. **HSTS Not Compiled**: The curl package in Debian bullseye lacks HSTS support entirely
+2. **Feature Absence**: The `--hsts` option is unsupported; vulnerable code path does not exist
+3. **Build Decision**: Debian maintainers did not enable HSTS (curl 7.74.0 defaults to HSTS off)
+4. **Cannot Exploit**: No code path exists to trigger the parallel HSTS cache overwrite
+
+---
+
+## **Evidence from Debian Security Tracker**
+
+Direct quote from [Debian Security Tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2023-23915):
+
+> **[bullseye] - curl `<ignored>` (curl is not built with HSTS support)**
+
+This official designation confirms that:
+- The vulnerability is **ignored** for bullseye (not flagged as needing fixes)
+- The reason is explicit: **HSTS support is not built**
+- Debian security team has already determined this is not a concern for bullseye
+
+---
+
+### **Recommended: Mark as False Positive**
+- Add CVE-2023-23915 to your scanner's false positive/exception list for Debian bullseye curl
+- Document the reasoning: "HSTS functionality not compiled in Debian bullseye build"
+- Reference the official Debian Security Tracker determination
+- Verify with `curl -V` (absence of HSTS in Features) or `curl --hsts file url` (unsupported)
+- Monitor for any changes in future Debian bullseye curl updates that might include HSTS support
+
+---
+**References:**
+- [Debian Security Tracker - CVE-2023-23915](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2023-23915)
+- [curl CVE-2023-23915 Advisory](https://curl.se/docs/CVE-2023-23915.html)
+--
+2.43.0
Description: CVE-2026-5773 - Fix wrong reuse of SMB connection across different shares
 libcurl incorrectly reused SMB connections across different shares due to
 the connkeep() call in smb_connect(). This could result in downloading the
 wrong file or uploading to the wrong location when using identical
 credentials and server names but different shares. The upstream fix
 (curl 8.20.0) removes PROTOPT_CONN_REUSE from SMB protocol handlers in
 lib/protocol.c. In curl 7.74.0, the equivalent mechanism is the
 connkeep() call in lib/smb.c which is replaced with connclose() to
 disable SMB connection reuse entirely.
Origin: backport, https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/74a169575d6412dc0ff532acdf94de35a6c2a571
Author: Daniel Stenberg <daniel@haxx.se>
Last-Update: 2026-05-01

--- a/lib/smb.c
+++ b/lib/smb.c
@@ -257,8 +257,8 @@ static CURLcode smb_connect(struct connectdata *conn, bool *done)
   if(!smbc->recv_buf)
     return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
 
-  /* Multiple requests are allowed with this connection */
-  connkeep(conn, "SMB default");
+  /* Do not reuse SMB connections across different shares */
+  connclose(conn, "SMB shares are not verified for reuse");
 
   /* Parse the username, domain, and password */
   slash = strchr(conn->user, '/');
