Description: CVE-2026-4873 - Do not reuse a non-TLS STARTTLS connection when TLS is required
 A logical flaw in curl's connection pooling mechanism allows a connection
 requiring TLS to incorrectly reuse an existing unencrypted connection from
 the same connection pool. This applies to IMAP, POP3, and SMTP protocols
 that support STARTTLS. When use_ssl is set to CURLUSESSL_CONTROL or higher
 (e.g. via --ssl-reqd), curl must not reuse a connection that has not been
 upgraded to TLS.
 .
 This is a manual backport of the upstream fix to the 7.74.0 codebase, which
 uses a monolithic ConnectionExists() function rather than the decomposed
 match functions in curl 8.x. The equivalent check is injected into
 ConnectionExists() after the existing PROTOPT_SSL flag comparison.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/507e7be573b0a76fca597b75ff7cb27a66e7d865
Author: Daniel Stenberg <daniel@haxx.se>
Last-Update: 2026-05-01

--- a/lib/url.c
+++ b/lib/url.c
@@ -1200,6 +1200,14 @@
           /* except protocols that have been upgraded via TLS */
           continue;
 
+      /* If both use a non-SSL protocol handler but the new request requires
+         TLS (e.g. --ssl-reqd on IMAP/POP3/SMTP), do not reuse a connection
+         that has not been upgraded to TLS via STARTTLS */
+      if(!(needle->handler->flags&PROTOPT_SSL) &&
+         !check->bits.tls_upgraded &&
+         (data->set.use_ssl >= CURLUSESSL_CONTROL))
+        continue;
+
 #ifndef CURL_DISABLE_PROXY
       if(needle->bits.httpproxy != check->bits.httpproxy ||
          needle->bits.socksproxy != check->bits.socksproxy)
